You are debugging a production issue where a high-throughput Spring Boot application experiences intermittent thread starvation and high DB connection pool latency. The application uses a custom registry to cache token metadata. Here is the simplified class snippet:

java
@Component
public class TokenRegistry {
    private final Map<String, Token> tokenCache = new ConcurrentHashMap<>();
    @Autowired
    private UserRepository userRepository;

    @Transactional(readOnly = true)
    public Token getOrCreateToken(String userId) {
        return tokenCache.computeIfAbsent(userId, id -> {
            User user = userRepository.findById(id)
                .orElseThrow(() -> new UserNotFoundException(id));
            return new Token(user);
        });
    }
}

During peak load, threads invoking `getOrCreateToken` block significantly, leading to database connection exhaustion.

You are debugging a production issue where an application suffers from a progressive heap memory leak, eventually throwing `OutOfMemoryError: Java heap space`. Profiling reveals that millions of `ClassLoader` instances are retained. The system uses a dynamic plugin loader that registers classloaders in a custom metadata cache defined as:

java
public class PluginMetadataCache {
    private final Map<ClassLoader, Map<String, Object>> cache = new WeakHashMap<>();

    public void register(ClassLoader loader, String key, Object value) {
        Map<String, Object> data = cache.computeIfAbsent(loader, k -> new HashMap<>());
        data.put(key, value);
    }
}

Here, the `value` object placed into the inner map is an instance of a class loaded by the corresponding `ClassLoader` key.

You are debugging a production issue where a custom Copy-on-Write list implementation causes sporadic `ArrayIndexOutOfBoundsException` and missed updates under high concurrent write volumes. The class and its custom iterator are implemented as follows:

java
public class CustomCopyOnWriteList<E> implements Iterable<E> {
    private volatile Object[] array = new Object[0];

    public synchronized void add(E element) {
        Object[] oldArray = array;
        Object[] newArray = Arrays.copyOf(oldArray, oldArray.length + 1);
        newArray[oldArray.length] = element;
        array = newArray;
    }

    public int size() { return array.length; }
    public E get(int index) { return (E) array[index]; }

    @Override
    public Iterator<E> iterator() {
        return new Iterator<>() {
            private int cursor = 0;
            @Override
            public boolean hasNext() { return cursor < size(); }
            @Override
            public E next() { return get(cursor++); }
        };
    }
}
